Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [46]:
# Write the code here
# Convert 'rating' column to numeric, forcing errors to NaN if conversion fails
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Group by 'restaurant_name' to calculate count of ratings and average rating
restaurant_group = df.groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
    rating_count=('rating', 'count'),
    average_rating=('rating', 'mean')
).reset_index()

# Filter restaurants based on conditions: rating count > 50 and average rating > 4
eligible_restaurants = restaurant_group[
    (restaurant_group['rating_count'] > 50) &
    (restaurant_group['average_rating'] > 4)
]

# Display the eligible restaurants
print("Restaurants eligible for the promotional offer:")
print(eligible_restaurants[['restaurant_name', 'rating_count', 'average_rating']])

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [49]:
# Write the code here
# Calculate commission for each order
def calculate_commission(order_cost):
    if order_cost > 20:
        return order_cost * 0.25
    elif order_cost > 5:
        return order_cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply the commission calculation to each order
df['commission'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_commission)

# Calculate the net revenue by summing all commissions
net_revenue = df['commission'].sum()

# Display the net revenue
print(f"Net revenue generated by the company: ${net_revenue:.2f}")

Net revenue generated by the company: $6166.30

Observations:¶

  • Revenue from Orders:
    • The analysis showed how the company generates revenue from orders based on different commission rates. The results provide an estimate of the company's revenue performance and help evaluate the efficiency of the commission model in use.

# Define which days are considered weekends
weekend_days = ['Saturday', 'Sunday']

  • Frequent Customers:

Cuisine and Order Preferences¶

  • Most Popular Cuisine:
    The most popular cuisine was identified, which provides insights into customer preferences.
    The company can use this information to feature specific cuisines in weekday promotions or collaborate with more restaurants offering these popular cuisines.

Order Value Analysis¶

  • Percentage of Orders Above $20:
    Knowing what percentage of orders cost more than $20 provides insights into customer spending behavior.
    It can also help set promotional strategies like discounts on high-value orders to increase the average order value.

Net Revenue Analysis¶

  • Revenue from Orders:
    The analysis showed how the company generates revenue from orders based on different commission rates.
    The results provide an estimate of the company's revenue performance and help evaluate the efficiency of the commission model in use.

Delivery Performance¶

  • Mean Delivery Time:
    The mean delivery times for weekdays and weekends were calculated, showing how delivery times might vary across different days.
    Shorter delivery times during weekends could indicate improved efficiency due to fewer orders or higher staffing levels.

    This could be targeted with optimizations like improved route planning, better preparation time management, or hiring more drivers.

Recommendations¶

  1. Enhance Delivery Efficiency

    • Optimize Delivery Routes:
      Implement a route optimization algorithm or partner with third-party services to ensure quicker and more reliable deliveries, particularly on weekdays when delivery times tend to be longer.
      (Note: This information might vary because we do NOT have weekend data entries).

    • Improve Preparation and Delivery Coordination:
      Coordinate better between restaurants and delivery partners to reduce the total delivery time, especially for orders taking more than 60 minutes.

    • Peak Time Resource Allocation:
      Increase delivery staff during peak hours when higher order volumes might cause delays in delivery.


  1. Customer Engagement and Loyalty Programs

    • Frequent Customer Incentives:
      Introduce a loyalty program for the top customers identified.
      Reward these customers with vouchers, discounts, or exclusive deals to maintain and enhance their loyalty.

    • Personalized Promotions:
      Use data on top cuisines during weekends to send targeted promotions and deals to customers based on their past order history and preferences.

    • Review and Ratings:
      Encourage customers to leave ratings and reviews after every order.
      Offer small discounts or loyalty points in exchange for reviews to help other users make informed choices.


  1. Restaurant Partnership and Performance Improvement

    • Partnerships with High-Performing Restaurants:
      Promote restaurants that meet the criteria for high ratings and a sufficient number of orders.
      Feature these restaurants prominently on the app to drive more traffic and improve overall customer satisfaction.

    • Training for Low-Performing Restaurants:
      Provide support and training to restaurants with low ratings to help them improve.
      Focus areas include food quality, preparation time, and delivery preparation time.

    • Incentive Programs for Restaurants:
      Create an incentive program for restaurants that meet high standards of food quality.
      Offer reduced commission fees or increased promotional opportunities for qualifying restaurants.
      (Note: Promotions like this might work, but they require commitment from restaurants and might need monitoring to ensure accuracy of information.)


  1. Pricing Strategy Optimization

    • Commission Tier Adjustments:
      Consider adjusting the commission structure based on order values.
      Currently, a 25% commission is applied for orders over $20 and 15% for smaller orders. Revisiting these thresholds may balance encouraging higher-order value while ensuring profitability for both FoodHub and partner restaurants.

    • High-Value Order Promotions:
      Encourage larger orders by offering discounts or value-added services such as free delivery for orders above a certain amount to increase the average order value.


  1. Operational Improvements Based on Data Insights

    • Improve Weekday Operations:
      Analyze staffing levels and operational practices to improve weekday delivery times.
      (Note: This must be checked with weekend data, as missing data may lead to biased conclusions. Weekend data needs to be revisited for proper evaluation.)

    • Data-Driven Inventory Management:
      Provide partner restaurants with insights from historical data to better manage inventory during peak demand, minimizing inefficiencies during high-volume periods.


  1. Marketing and Promotions

    • Highlight Popular Cuisines:
      Use marketing campaigns to promote popular cuisines on weekends, offering special deals to increase weekend orders.

    • New Customer Offers:
      Attract new customers with introductory and specific promotions.


  1. Customer Feedback and Continuous Improvement

    • Implement Feedback Mechanisms:
      Collect feedback from customers, partner restaurants, and delivery drivers to help improve service quality systematically.

  1. Optimize Preparation and Delivery for Large Orders

    • Large Order Management:
      Implement strategies to efficiently process large orders, such as batching deliveries or prioritizing kitchen preparation.

    • Improvement in Delivery Allocation:
      Use an intelligent algorithm to prioritize deliveries for large orders, reducing waiting time and increasing customer satisfaction.


Summary of Data Collection and Revisiting Data Analysis¶

  • Missing Weekend Data:
    During the exploration of the data and the EDA process, we found that there was missing information regarding orders on weekends.
    This gap in data is crucial as it impacts the completeness of the analysis.
    Weekends are high-demand days, and without weekend data, our conclusions could be biased or incomplete.
    This is especially important for FoodHub since the business relies heavily on understanding both user growth (end customers) and business growth (partner restaurants).

  • Impact on Analysis:

    • Missing weekend data affects conclusions related to customer satisfaction, restaurant partnerships, delivery efficiency, and targeted promotions.
    • It is essential to capture data from weekends to make more informed decisions about operations, promotional strategies, and optimizing service.

  • Key Areas Affected:

    • Customer Growth and Satisfaction: Understanding weekend behavior is key to enhancing customer loyalty.
    • Operational Efficiency: Weekends are high-volume periods, requiring insights to optimize staffing, delivery times, and order handling.
    • Business Partnerships: Partner restaurants may need support or incentives to improve performance during high-demand times.
